<DOC><DOCNO> AP890520-0017 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0152EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     05-20 0654</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,650</SECOND><HEAD>Drug Testing Plan Blocked</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Plans to administer drug tests to 30 employeesin the executive office of the president and hundreds of workers inthe General Services Administration have been temporarily blockedby a federal judge.   U.S. District Court Judge Louis Oberdorfer issued a preliminaryinjunction Friday against the random, mandatory testing which wasto have begun as early as next week.   He said the programs may be overly broad and there is littleevidence in the court record of any drug problem among employeescovered by the programs.   The judge also temporarily enjoined testing of GSA employeessuspected of using drugs. The agency's plan must first be revisedto provide that testing is based on more specific requirements,``reasonable, articulable and individualized suspicion,'' he said.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Lucas Working at Justice</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Even before he has been formally approved, thecontroversial nominee to head the Bush administration's civilrights program is working at the Justice Department.   William Lucas is working as a $284-a-day consultant whileawaiting Senate confirmation as assistant attorney general forcivil rights, the department said Friday.   Lucas, whose nomination is opposed by some civil rights groups,is studying the Justice Department's role in training lawenforcement officials to be sensitive about civil-rights issues andreport potential violations, said David Runkel, chief JusticeDepartment spokesman.   The consulting agreement, which took effect March 20, is acommon arrangement for Bush administration officials awaitingSenate action on their nominations, Runkel said.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Prosecutors Say North Wasn't Convicted on Immunized Testimony</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The evidence used to convict Oliver North wasgathered independently from the former White House aide's immunizedcongressional testimony given two years ago, according toprosecutors.   The government made the assertion in a federal court filingurging rejection of North's request for a post-trial hearing on theissue.   In his testimony on Capitol Hill, North detailed many of theactivities for which he was later accused of crimes, including thethree felonies for which he was ultimately convicted.   North's lawyers want the case against him dismissed. They havesaid the grand jury that indicted him and the jury that convictedhim might have been tainted by exposure to his immunized testimony.Prosecutors disputed that in a response filed on Friday.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Experts Score Bush Sandamp;L Rescue Plan</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush's savings and loan bailout planis a ``banana republic'' scheme that will cost taxpayers $30billion to $50 billion more than a Democratic alternative,according to some Wall Street experts.   The extra expense of paying for the bailout through 30-year,off-budget bonds to preserve the illusion of deficit reduction willlikely be 10 times the $3.8 billion to $4.5 billion theadministration has acknowledged, a special House panel was toldFriday.   ``This is an incredible price to pay for budgetary windowdressing,'' said Bert Ely, who heads a financial consulting firm inAlexandria, Va. ``Billions of dollars can be saved if the cleanupis funded for a few years with short-term borrowings untillong-term rates decline.''   Comptroller General Charles Bowsher, head of the government'sGeneral Accounting Office, agreed with Ely and representatives ofWall Street investment houses that Bush's Sandamp;L plan will tax thepublic tens of billions of dollars in unnecessary interest costs.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Special Office Created for Reactor Restart</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A supervisory office at the troubled SavannahRiver nuclear weapons plant in South Carolina to improve the EnergyDepartment's oversight of the aging complex.   Energy Secretary James Watkins announced the establishmentFriday of a Special Projects Office, starting June 1, at SavannahRiver. Its director will report directly to the assistant secretaryfor defense programs at department headquarters.   The three Savannah River reactors, which make a gas used innuclear warheads, have been shut down for safety reasons since lastspring. Watkins has said he intends to get them running again byearly next year.</TEXT></DOC>